    <note>Lu(5) Zhi [1284] His ancestors were Wujun Lu(5). At the end of the Tang, they moved from Wujun, Jiaxing (then a part of Suzhou) to Hangzhou, Qiantang. At the time of the Wuyue kings, they moved to Shaoxing, Shanyin xian. In 1012, Gui's [7049] father, Zhen [3634], used the jinshi to establish this family (qijia) branch of the lineage. Zhi was Dian's [8098] son, Gui's [7049] grandson, Zai's [1288] brother, and Zhuan's [7297] and Bi's [7051] nephew. He moved to Mingzhou to avoid the disorder of the early Southern Song. Lin(1) Bao [1165] was his sons' (Guang's [3635] and Liu's [3636]) father-in-law. One of Guang's sons-in-law was Zhan(1) Qi [3115], who had the generational name of the Shaoxing, Shaoxing-s Zhan(1) Qi and the other son-in-law, Geng(1) Kai [3467], was supervisor of the Chuzhou, Yancheng xian Salt Market (Yanchang) in ca. 1195. Yuan [3641], another of Zhi's sons, was Tiju Liangzhe shibo and Tiju Fujian shibo between 1167 and 1173. Yuan's son-in-law, Lou(2) Jun [3616], who was supervisor of the grain procurement market (Dichang) of the Huaidong zonglingsuo in ca. 1195, was a son or nephew of Lou(2) Shou [1265]. Fujian TZ, 32.17a; XNYL, 73.8a; Lu You, WJ, 34.7b, 35.2a; Bao Siming, 8.30a; SHY:ZG, 42.43b, 69.21a-21b; SHY:SH, 49.33a. CBD, 3, 2657.</note>
